{
  "local_port": 38690,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My iPhone screen broke I have iCloud, would notifications I received transfer over to a replacement or would contacts transfer and notifications gone?",
  "response": "I'm sorry to hear about your broken iPhone screen. Let's address your concerns regarding data transfer when setting up a replacement iPhone using iCloud:\n\n### **1. Contacts:**\n- **Transfer Status:** **Will Transfer**\n- **Details:** If you have **iCloud Contacts** enabled, all your contacts are synced and stored in your iCloud account. When you set up your new iPhone and sign in with your Apple ID, your contacts will automatically sync to the new device. Ensure that iCloud Contacts is turned on by going to **Settings > [Your Name] > iCloud** and verifying that the **Contacts** toggle is enabled.\n\n### **2. Notifications:**\n- **Transfer Status:** **Will Not Transfer**\n- **Details:** Notifications are generally **transient** and are not stored or backed up by iCloud. They represent real-time alerts from apps and services on your device. Here's what happens with notifications:\n  - **Past Notifications:** These do **not** transfer to your new iPhone. Notifications you received on your old device won't appear on the replacement device.\n  - **Future Notifications:** After setting up your new iPhone, you'll receive new notifications as usual, provided your notification settings are correctly configured.\n\n### **Additional Data Transfers via iCloud:**\nWhen you restore your new iPhone from an iCloud backup, several types of data and settings are transferred, including:\n- **Apps and App Data:** Most apps and their data will reinstall and sync if they support iCloud.\n- **Photos and Videos:** If you use **iCloud Photos**, your media will sync to the new device.\n- **Messages:** If **Messages in iCloud** is enabled, your iMessages and SMS messages will sync.\n- **Settings:** Wi-Fi settings, wallpaper, and other system preferences will be restored.\n- **Calendars, Reminders, Notes, etc.:** These will also sync if they're enabled in iCloud.\n\n### **Steps to Set Up Your New iPhone:**\n1. **Power On:** Turn on your new iPhone.\n2. **Start Setup:** Follow the on-screen instructions until you reach the **Apps & Data** screen.\n3. **Restore from iCloud Backup:** Choose **Restore from iCloud Backup**.\n4. **Sign In:** Enter your Apple ID and password.\n5. **Choose Backup:** Select the most recent backup from your broken iPhone.\n6. **Complete Setup:** Wait for the restore process to complete. Ensure you're connected to Wi-Fi and have sufficient battery or are plugged in.\n\n### **Tips:**\n- **Verify Backup:** Before setting up the new iPhone, you can check if your old iPhone was backed up to iCloud by visiting **Settings > [Your Name] > iCloud > Manage Storage > Backups** on another Apple device or via [iCloud.com](https://www.icloud.com).\n- **Enable Necessary Syncs:** After setup, double-check that services like Contacts, Photos, and others are enabled in **Settings > [Your Name] > iCloud**.\n\n### **Final Note:**\nWhile your essential data like contacts, photos, and app data will transfer seamlessly, **notification history** is not part of the iCloud backup and thus won't be available on the new device. However, your device will be set up to receive new notifications from your apps as usual.\n\nIf you have any more questions or need further assistance during the setup process, feel free to ask!",
